column168: LEFFLER UNIT WAS EMPTY AFTER DELIVERING A LOAD OF GASOLINE.  THE LEFFLER UNIT WAS STRUCK BY A TRACTOR FLATBED TRAILER THAT HAD CROSSED IN TO HIS LANE.  THE IMPACT KNOCKED THE TANK FROM THE CHASSIS.  THE TANK LANDED 30 FEET FROM IMPACY.  THE FRONT COMPARTMENT WAS PUNCTURED FROM THE IMPACT. THE REAR COMPARTMENT WAS RUPTURED BY THE HOSE REEL.  FUEL FROM WET LINES WAS BURING AND IGNITED THE ESCAPING FUMES.  AN ESTIMATED 100 GALLONS OF RESIDUAL PRODUCT WAS IN THE LINES AND COMPARTMENTS.  ALL PRODUCT WAS BURNED DURING THE FIRE. BOTH UNITS INVOLVED IN THE ACCIDENT ARE A TOTAL LOSS, EITHER BY FIRE OR DAMAGE FROM IMPACT.  BOTH DRIVERS WERE TREATED AT THE HOSPITAL AND RELEASED.  INJURIES WERE SUSTAINED DUE TO THE COLLISION, NOT FROM THE RELEASE OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.

DISPOSAL CONTROL SERVICES EVENTUALLY REMOVED DICHLORMETHANE AS PER ATTACHED HAZARDOUS WASTE MANIFEST COPY.

GLASS NEEDS CUSHIONING DURING NORMAL TRANSIT TO PREVENT FAILURES.

column168: DURING A GASOLINE DELIVERY TO BARRINGTON, ILLINOIS SERVICE STATION, A DELIVERY HOSE RUPTURED CAUSING A SPILL OF APPROXIMATELY 100 GALLONS OF SUPER UNLEADED GASOLINE.  DUE TO THE INCLINE OF THE PROPERTY, THE SPILLED PRODUCT FLOWED OFF THE PROPERTY AND ALONG THE CURB ONTO NORTHWEST HIGHWAY ENTERING 3 STORM WATER CATCH BASINS. THE BARRINGTON FIRE DEPT., WHO RESPONDED IMMEDIATELY, USED OIL DRY AND ABSORBENTS TO ABSORB THE GASOLINE ALONGSIDE THE CURB.  THEY ALSO DAMMED UP THE STORM DRAINS OPENINGS TO PREVENT FURTHER ENTRY OF GASOLINE.  BOTH FEDERAL AND STATE AGENCIES WERE NOTIFIED AND A CONTRACTOR WAS CALLED IN TO REMOVE PRODUCT/WATER FROM THE 3 CATCH BASINS VIA SUCTION TRUCK.  AN ANALYSIS OF THE SUBJECT DELIVERY HOSE IS UNDERWAY TO DETERMINE CAUSE OF RUPTURE.

E RAYHA THEN NEUTRALIZED THE REMAINING LIQUID WITH SODIUM BICARBONATE AND SOLIDIFIED THE MIXTURE WITH SOLUSORB.  HE THEN BAGGED, BOXED AND DISPOSED OF THE SOLIDIFIED MATTER IN THE DESIGNATED DUMPSTER.  THE SHIPPER SHOULD CONSIDER PURCHASING STRONGER PLASTIC JUGS TO WITHSTAND A GREAT AMOUNT OF INTERNAL PRESSURE CAUSED BY SEVERE TEMPERATURE CHANGE.

column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 1800 EST AN ASSOCIATED COURIERS DRIVER WAS INSIDE MEDI-PHYSICS AT 2000 SULLIVAN ROAD, COLLEGE PARK, GA. ONE OF THE MEDI-PHYSICS EMPLOYEES TOLD OUR DRIVER THAT "SOMEONE WAS FOOLING AROUND WITH HIS TRUCK". OUR DRIVER RUSHED OUTSIDE JUST IN TIME TO SEE HIS TRUCK BEING DRIVEN AWAY BY A PERSON OR PERSONS UNKNOWN. THE TRUCK HAD BEEN LOCKED AND THE KEYS WERE IN THE DRIVER'S POCKET. THE POLICE WERE CALLED AS WERE THE NATIONAL EMERGENCY RESPONSE CENTER AND THE STATE OF GEORGIA DEPARTMENT OF NATURAL RESOURCES. THE TRUCK HAS NOT BEEN FOUND TO DATE. THE PACKAGES WERE FOUND WITHIN THE CITY LIMITS OF ATLANTA IN THE PARKING LOT OF PIONEER NEON SUPPLY AT 1356 ENGLISH NW. ALL OF THE 29 PACKAGES WERE RECOVERED. SEVERAL OF THE PACKAGES WERE TORN OPEN AND 5 OF THE RADIOACTIVE DIAGNOSTIC SOURCES WERE FOUND TO BE MISSING. MISSING WERE 3 T1-201 (THALLOUS CHLORIDE) SOURCES AT 27 MILLICURIES EACH AND 2 T1-201 (THALLOUS CHLORIDE) SOURCES AT 16 MILLICURIES EACH. THESE SOURCES HAVE NOT BEEN RECOVERED TO DATE.

column168: END DUMP TRAILER IS LINED WITH A PACTECH (BRAND) DUMP BED LINER.  THIS LINER IS A SPECIAL BLEND OF BOTH HIGH AND LOW DENSITY POLY ETHYLENE MATERIALS WHICH RESULTS IN A SUPER STRONG LINER.  CRUSHED DRUMS ARE THEN LOWERED INTO THE TRAILER BY AN ELECTRO-MAGNET.  THE LINER IS OVERLAPED AND FOLDED OVER TOP OF DRUMS THEN TAPED AND TAILGATE SAFETY CHAINS ATTACHED TO END GATE.  THIS LOAD WAS TRANSPORTED ON THE 27TH OF DECEMBER.  DURING TRANSPORTATION THE DRIVER STATED THAT RAINFALL WAS EXTREMELY HEAVY FOR ALMOST THE ENTIRE TRIP.  WHEN THE DRIVER CROSSED THE SCALES AT THE CHEMICAL WASTE FACILITY, THE SECURITY GUARD ADVISED THE DRIVER THAT THE TRAILER WAS LEAKING.  A CAN WAS PLACED TO CATCH THE LEAK AND SPILLED MATERIAL WAS ABSORBED WITH ABSORBENT THEN DISPOSED OF WITH OF REMAINDER OF LEAD.  THE TARP HAD FOUR SMALL RIPS IN IT WHICH HAD ALLOWED RAINWATER INTO THE DUMP BODY.  THIS WATER HAD REMAINED OUTSIDE THE LINER AND WAS CAUSED TO LEAK FROM THE REAR OF THE TRAILER (END GATE) IMMEDIATELY PRIOR TO CROSSING THE TSD FACILITY SCALES.  THE ENTRANCE TO SCALES IS AN INCLINE WHICH CAUSED THE SMALL AMOUNT OF WATER TO MOVE TO THE REAR OF THE DUMP AREA, AT WHICH POINT IT DRIPPED FROM THE DUMP BODY.  DRIVER STATED THAT HE SAW NO OIL OR OTHER MATERIAL IN LEAKAGE, ONLY WHAT APEARED TO BE WATER. ACTION TO PREVENT REOCCURRENCE: 1. MORE THOROUGH INSPECTION OF END DUMP TARPS, 2.  PLACEMENT OF ABSORBENT AT END GATE TO ABSORD ANY WATER OR OIL. (SOME RESIDUE REMAINS IN THE CRUSHED DRUMS THAT COULD LEAK IF LINER IS PUNCTURED).

column168: SWITHC CREW ENTERED PLANT TO PULL TWO TANK CARS THAT WERE RELEASED FOR TRANSPORTATION.  THE INSTANT TANK CAR, IAPX 1005, WAS SPOTTED BETWEEN THESE TWO CARS AND WAS TO BE RESPOTTED FOR UNLOADING.  THE CARS WERE INSPECTD ON THE EAST SIDE, BUT BECAUSE OF HEAVY VAPOR FOG, CREW MEMBER DID NOT WALK ON WEST SIDE OF CARS. IAPX 1005 WAS CONNECTED BY A THREE-INCH HOSE FOR PRODUCT DISCHARGE WHICH WAS NOT DISCONNECTED BEFORE CAR WAS PULLED.  AS A RESULT, A NIPPLE ON THE OUTLET VALVE BROKE OFF AND ALLOWED LIQUID OXYGEN TO FLOW FROM THE CAR FOR APPROXIMATELY TEN MINUTED BEFORE TRAIL CREW CLOSED THE VALVE.  NO BLUE SIGN OR WHEEL CHOCKS WERE IN PLACE NOR WAS THE UNLOADING ATTENDANT NEAR THE CAR WHEN PULLED.

OUR DRIVER WAS CLEARED FOR DELIVERY AT DESTINATION AND PROCEEDED TO ARRANGE FOR TRANSFER OF THE PRODUCT TO THE CUSTOMER'S STORAGE TANK.  WHEN STARTED TO TRANSFER HE NOTED THAT ONE OF HIS FITTINGS WAS LEAKING.  HE SHUT DOWN AND IN ATTEMPTING TO BLEED PRESSURE FROM HIS HOSES HE WAS SPRAYED WITH THE PRODUCT.  HE WAS WEARING FULL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT BUT SOME OF THE MATERIAL RAN DOWN INTO HIS GLOVE AND BURNED HIS HAND.  HE FLUSHED THE AREA WITH WATER AND WAS TREATED AND RELEASED AT A LOCAL CLINIC.

OUR DRIVER WAS CLEARED FOR DELIVERY.  HE CONNECTED THE UNLOADING HOSE AND THE CUSTOMER'S PUMP ALONG WITH NITROGEN PRESSURE WAS BEING USED TO TRANSFER THE MATERIAL. WHEN THE TRANSFER WAS COMMENCED IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT A FITTING WAS LEAKING AND THE PUMP WAS STOPPED AND THE VALVES ON THE TRAILER CLOSED.  THE UNLOADER THEN DISCONNECTED THE HOSE WITHOUT BLEEDING THE PRESSURE AND PRODUCT IN THE HOSE SPRAYED OUT STRIKING THE DRIVER AS WELL AS THE UNLOADER.  A SMALL AMOUNT OF MATERIAL REACHED THE SKIN OF BOTH INDIVIDUALS AND AFTER FLUSHING WITH WATER THEY WERE TREATED AT THE PLANT DISPENSARY.

column168: DRIVER WAS EN ROUTE TO USPCI (GRASSY MOUNTAIN, UT) WITH A FLATBED TRAILER CONTAINING DRUMS FOR USPCI AND THE SUBJECT CONTAINER, TO BE DELIVERED ON RETURN TRIP TOP FERNLEY, NV.  IN EASTERN NV, DRIVER ENCOUNTERED SNOW AND FREEZING CONDITIONS.  HE BAGAN TO STOP EVERY HALF HOUR TO CHECK HIS VEHICLE AND LOAD.  AFTER SEVERAL SUCH CHECKS, HE REACHED WENDOVER, NV AND STOPPED TO PERFORM ANOTHER INSPECTION.  AT THAT TIME (0900), HE NOTICED LIQUID LEAKING FROM A SMALL CRACK NEAR THE BOTTOM OF THE CONTAINER VERTICAL, ABOUT 1-2 INCHES LOING.  DRIVER PULLED OUT OF TRAFFIC INTO A SOIL & GRAVEL PARKING AREA; CALLED CO. DISPATCH OFFICE.  OFFICE CONTACTED A CLEAN-UP CONTRACTOR IN SALT LAKE CITY AREA.  RESPONSED AND FULL CLEAN-UP TOOK- 6 HOURS.  6-8 DRUMS OF SOIL SHIPPED TO USPCI.  DEPUTY SHERIFF ON SCENE ACKNOWLEDGED THAT NO ADDITIONAL CONTAMINATION WAS LEFT.
DRIVER WAS PUMPING OUT A STORAGE TANK WHEN HE DISCONNECTED HOSE WHILE NEGLECTING TO CLOSE HIS INTERNAL VALVES.  FUEL RUSHED OUT AND BEFORE HE COULD CLOSE VALVES, 933 GALLONS OF FUEL WAS SPILLED.

column168: OUR DRIVER WAS HEADING SOUTH ON U.S.23 WHEN HE APPROACHED THE INTERSECTION OF U.S.23 & KY. 1428.  THE LIGHT WAS GREEN FOR THE TRAFFIC ON U.S. 23.  AS OUR DRIVER ENTERED THE INTERSECTION A CAR TRAVELLING AT A HIGH RATE OF SPEED RAN THE RED LIGHT STRIKING OUR TRUCK IN THE RIGHT FRONT CORNER CAUSING IT TO SWERVE AND OVERTURN.  IT SLID ON IT'S SIDE ACROSS THE MEDIAN INTO THE NORTH BOUND LANE OF U.S. 23 COMING TO REST THERE.  DURING THIS THE TANK WAS RUPTURED CAUSING TH ELOAD OF DIESEL FUEL TO SPILL.  EYE WITNESS GAVE THE K.S.P. WRITTEN STATEMENTS THAT THE DRIVER OF THE CAR ENTERED THE INTERSECTION WITHOUT MAKING ANY ATTEMPT TO STOP AT THE RED LIGHT.  THE DRIVER OF THE CAR WAS KILLED DUE TO THE ACCIDENT.  WE HOLE SAFETY MEETINGS AND HAVE TRAINING CLASSES ON A REGULAR BASES TO TRY AND EDUCATE OUR PEOPLE ON WHAT TO DO IN THE CASE OF ACCIDENTS LIKE THIS.    *KENTUKY  D.E.S. WAS ON THE SCENE OF THE ACCIDENT.

column168: DRIVER HAD HOOKED UP HOSES AND WAS IN THE PROCESS OF MAKING A DELIVERY OF GASOLINE.  AN AUTOMOBILE PULLED AWAY FROM THE PUMPS AT A HIGH RATE OF SPEED AND STRUCK THE UNLOADING LINE.  THE IMPACT PUSHED THE HOSE COMPLETELY OFF THE CONNECTION AND A SPARK IGNITED FROM THE UNDERCARRIAGE OF THE AUTOMOBILE.  THE FIRE SPREAD ALMOST IMMEDIATELY UP THE HOSE AND TO THE FRONT OF THE TRAILER.  THE FIRE DEPARTMENT CONTAINED THE FLAMES AND THE MAJORITY OF THE DAMAGE WAS TO THE TRACTOR/TRAILER AND AUTOMOBILE. IT IS ESTIMATED THAT SOME PRODUCT DID SPILL INTO THE SEWER.  THE FIRE DEPARTMENT FLUSHED THE AREA AND VERIFIED NO VAPORS IN AREA BASEMENTS. THE INCIDENT IS STILL UNDER INVESTIGATION.  ALL REGULATORY AGENCIES WERE NOTIFIED AND WERE ON-SITE.

LEAKAGE DISCOVERD AT TIME OF DELIVERY TO CONSIGNEE.  CONSIGNEE HAS HAZMAT EQUIPMENT AND PEOPLE ON SITE AND RESPONDED TO THIS LEAK UPON DETECTION. 5 GALLON PAIL WAS PLACED IN RECOVERY DRUM AND IS BEING HELD AT CONSIGNEE LOCATION.  TRAILER WAS RETURNED TO TERMINAL IN RIVIERA BEACH, FL FOR CLEAN UP OF ABSORBENT ON HARDWOOD TRAILER FLOOR.  TRAILER WAS CLEANED BY HOUSEHOLD BLEACH AND WATER FOR DILUTION OF ANY AMOUNT SOAKED IN FLOOR OF TRAILER.  ABSORBENT THAT WAS REMOVED FROM THE TRAILER WAS PLACED IN A 5 GALLON PAIL, THEN LATER DILUTED WITH WATER AND USED FOR WEED CONTROL AT FENCE LINE OF PROPERTY.

EMPLOYEE TRIED TO SQUARE SKID UP BY USING TOWMOTOR.  THE ONE PUNCTURED BOX WAS SLIGHTLY OVER HANGING.  EMPLOYEE'S BOOM OF FORKS, HE STRUCK BOX CAUSING PUNCTURE. WHEN DISCOVERED PLACED ABSORBENT AROUND SPILL, REMOVED PUNCTURED BOX FROM SKID AND VACATED AREA.  THEN CALLED HAZ. MATERIAL TEAM. EMPLOYEE WAS GIVEN DISCIPLINE AND OTHER EMPLOYEE'S WERE AGAIN INSTRUCTED ON PROPER HANDLING OF HAZ. MATERIAL.  HAZ. MATERIAL WHEN PUT ON PALLETS SHOULD BE MADE AWARE NOT WITH ANY PROTRUDING PARTS.

column168: MONDAY, DECEMBER 31, 1990 AT APPROXIMATELY 2:15 P.M. A SPILL OF MID-GRADE (PLUS) GASOLINE OCCURRED AT THE REFERENCE FACILITY DURING TANK FILLING FROM A TRANSPORT.  THE FILL ELBOW HAS A SECONDARY FITTING DESIGNED AS A CONNECTION FOR A STAGE 1 VAPOR RETURN HOSE.  THIS FITTING WAS CAPPED SINCE VAPOR RECOVERY IS NOT REQUIRED AT THIS FACILITY.  THE CAP APPARENTLY WAS NOT PROPERLY SECURED AS IT DISLOGED AND RESULTED IN A SPILL OF 245 GALLONS (COMPUTED FROM BEFORE AND AFTER STICK READINGS AND LOADING MANIFEST).  THE FRANKFORT FIRE DEPT. RESPONDED AND SPREAD A MIXTURES OF SAND AND OIL DRY TO ABSORB FREE PRODUCT.  CHIEF DEPUTY STATE FIRE MARSHALL MORGAN KELLY ALSO RESPONDED AND COMMUNICATED WITH DAVID KENDALL, K P DISPATCHER, BY TELEPHONE.  KENTUCKY PUMP AND TANK COMPANY WAS DISPATCHED TO THE FACILITY AT APPROXIMATELY 3;30 P.M. WITH A BACKHOE.  AN UNPAVED AREA TO THE REAR OF THE TANK SLAB WAS EXCAVATED TO A DEPTH OF 12" TO 24" AND ABOUT 30 SQUARE FEET AND DEPOSITED ON PLASTIC SHEELTS AND COVERED.  ON WEDNESDAY. JANUARY 2, 1991 I MET WITH LARRY ENGLE OF SPADE CORPORATION, GEORGETOWN.  KENTUCKY TO DETERMINE FURTHER ACTION.  SAMPLES OF THE SPOIL PILE WILL BE SENT TO THE LABORATORY FOR ANALYSIS WITH THE INTENT OF HAULING IT TO THE LANDFILL. SEVERAL BORE HOLES WILL BE DRILLED IN TH AREA AND ANLYZED FOR BTEX, THOUGH A VISUAL INSPECTION OF THE SITE REVEALED NO ON-GOING PROBLEM.

column168: AT 0124, ON 12-07-90, SORT SUPERVISOR MARSHA ADKINS, REPORTED AN ODOR COMING FROM A CARGO CONTAINER AT DOOR A-10 AT OUR MAIN SORT FACILITY.  CERT 4, TONY FRYE, AND CERT 14, RANDY WILLIAMS, DONNED A CARTRIDGE MASK AND STARTED INVESTIGATING THE CARGO CONTAINER.  FOUND INSIDE THE CONTAINER WERE THREE LARGE BLUE PLASTIC BAGS CONTAINING FREIGHT.  ONE OF THE BAGS WAS FOUND TO HAVE 25 FIBREBOARD BOXES LABELED, PAINT, FLAMMABLE LIQUID, UN1263.  SEEING THIS, WE TRANSPORTED THE SHIPMENT TO THE HAZ-MAT SORT FOR FURTHER INVESTIGATION.  FURTHER INVESTIGATING, WE OPENED ALL 25 FIBREBOARD BOXES.  INSIDE THE FIBREBOARD BOXES WERE 1 QT., METAL, FRICTION TYPE CONTAINERS.  ALL THE ONE QUART METAL CANS WERE PKGD. ON THEIR SIDE AGAINST PROPER ORIENTATION.  THREE OF THE 1-QT. METAL CANS WERE LEAKING POSSIBLY DUE TO OUTAGE OR IMPROPER ORIENTATION.  ALSO, 4 OF THE 1-QT. METAL CANS DID NOT HAVE ANY POSITIVE MEANS TO SECURE THE CLOSURES.  THE REMAINDER OF THE 1-QT. METAL CANS DID HAVE CLIPS TO SECURE THE CLOSURES.  THERE WAS PROPER DOCUMENTATION ACCOMPANYING THIS SHIPMENT.  ONE OF THE FIBREBOARD BOXES WERE LOADED ON ITS SIDE INSIDE THE BLUE BAG.  THIS SHIPMENT IS UNDER LOCK AND KEY IN THE HAZ-MAT SORT SECURITY CAGE UNTIL IT IS RELEASED BY THE FAA.

ONE LEAKING 5 GAL. DRUM WAS DISCOVERED WHILE UNLOADING AT THE SHIPLEY CO., IN MARLBORO, MA. ON 12-03-90 AT APPROXIMATELY 1605 HRS.  THE DRUM CONTAINED SODIUM PROMANGANATE 40% AND WAS IN THE MIDDLE ON THE TOP TIER OF A STRETCHED WRAPPED PALLET. APPARENTLY THE METAL WIRE HANDLE HAD BEEN STRUCK DURING LOADING OR UNLOADING PRIOR TO ARRIVING AT THE FARMINGHAM TERMINAL.  THE IMPACT BROKE THE SEAL AROUND THE LID AND ALLOWED APPROXIMATELY 1/2 TO 1 PINT OF SODIUM PROMANGANATE 40% TO LEAK OUT DURING TRANSPORT.  THE SODIUM PROMANGANATE CONTAMINATED SOME OF THE OTHER DRUMS, STRETCH WRAP AND THE SKID.  NO HM LIQUID TOUCHED THE TRAILER FLOOR. ENVIRONMENTAL SPECIALIST FROM SPRINGFIELD, MA. WERE CALLED TO THE SCENE WHERE THEY CLEANED AND DISPOSED OF THE SKID AND STRETCH WRAP. THE REMAINING 5 GAL. DRUMS WERE ALSO CLEANED AND ACCEPTED BY THE CONSIGNEE. THE LEAKING DRUM WAS PLACED IN A PROPER HM CONTAINER BY ENVIRONMENTAL SPECIALISTS AND BROUGHT BACK TO THE TERMINAL.  IT HAS BEEN RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER - CARUS CHEMICAL CO. THE DRIVER MARK WEBBER COMPLAINED OF SORE THROAT AND A HEADACHE APPARENTLY FROM INHALING FUMES FROM THE SPILL.  HE WAS TREATED AT UNIVERSITY OF MA. MEDICAL CENTER ON 12/4/90.  HE RETURNED TO WORK ON 12/5/90 WITH A FULL RELEASE FROM THE DOCTOR.

A LANTER COURIER GUARD PICKED UP 4 BOXES AT DOSKOCIL ON 12/5/90 AT 16:20 AND BROUGHT THEM BACK TO OUR WAREHOUSE & UNLOADED HIS TRUCK.  THE BOXES WERE WEIGHED AND SET ON THE FLOOR.  THIS IS WHEN 1 OF THE BOXES BROKE WITH FLUID LEAKING OUT OF THE BOTTOM.  I WAS NOTIFIED OF THIS SPILL BY SCOTT LEWINDOWSKI AT 20:00. AT THIS POINT I OPENED ONE OF THE OTHER BOXES WHICH DIDN'T BREAK & FOUND A 4 LITER BOTTLE OF BENZENE.  ASSUMING THE SPILL WAS BENZENE, I THEN CALLED OUR HAZARDOUS MATERIALS DEPARTMENT & TALKED TO KAREN NICHOLS.  AFTER TALKING WITH KAREN I WAS TOLD TO CONTAIN THE SPILL AND CLEAR THE IMMEDIATE AREA.  I THEN WENT OUT TO THE DOCK & TOOK ALL OF THE BROKEN BOTTLES OUT OF THE BOX & PUT THE REMAINDER IN A PLASTIC BAG. APPROXIMATELY FIVE MINUTES LATER I RECEIVED A CALL FROM KAREN ASKING WHAT I HAD DONE & I TOLD HER;  AT WHICH POINT SHE INSTRUCTED ME TO CALL OUR LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT.  ONCE THE FIRE DEPT. ARRIVED THEY EVACUATED THE BUILDING IMMEDIATELY AND SENT EVERYONE INVOLVED TO THE HOSPITAL FOR CHECK-UPS.

column168: ON 12/07/90, SENIOR SPECIAL AGENT/HAZARDOUS MATERIALS (SSA/HM) T. SMITH WAS NOTIFIED THAT TANK CAR TILX 100313 HAD LIQUID ON THE SIDE.  CAR WAS ISOLATED AND SSA/HM SMITH OBSERVED THAT THE FRANGIBLE DISK (100 LB STAINLESS STEEL) NEEDED REPLACING.  SA/HM SMITH AND SPECIAL AGENT MEADOWS REPLACED THE STAINLESS STEEL FRANGIBLE DISC AND SECURED THE CAR FOR MOVEMENT. CONSIGNEE AND SHIPPER WERE NOTIFIED AND INFORMED OF THE PROBLEM AND ACTION TAKEN.  THE SPILL WAS LESS THAN ONE GALLON AND NO PRODUCT REACHED THE GROUND.

column168: ON 12/01/90, MANAGER HAZARDOUS MATERIAL EMERGENCY RESPONSE R. M. STINE WAS CONTACTED BY CAR FOREMAN RICHARD MONGER, ADVISING RAIX 6079 WAS DRIPPING PRODUCT FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET. R. M. STINE AND DIRECTOR, HAZARDOUS MATERIAL MANAGEMENT LEO TIERNEY INSPECTED AND FOUND THE BOTTOM OUTLET CAP AND TWO INCH PLUG WAS LESS THAN WRENCH TIGHT.  CAR WAS EQUIPPED WITH A BOTTOM OPERATED OUTLET VALVE WHICH WAS IN THE CLOSED POSITION.  AFTER SECURING THE CAP AND PLUG, LEAK STOPPED AND CAR WAS RELEASED.

column17: CARMAN J A TRUCKING CO INC
column168: VII & VIII ABOVE; THERE WAS NO PACKING FAILURE OF ANY KIND.  WE WERE DISPATCHED BY TRIWELL MARKETING TO DILIVER 7000 GALLONS OF #2 FUEL OIL TO JEFFERSONVILLE CENTRAL SCHOOL.  UPON ARRIVAL, OUR DRIVER CONFIRMED WITH SCHOOL BOILERMAN THAT THE LOAD WOULD FIT.  WITH 840 GALLONS STILL ON OUR TANKER, THE STORAGE TANK OVERFILLED AND +- 5 GALLONS CAOME OUT AROUND THE FILL PIPE AND SPILLED ONTO THE BLACKTOP.  SPILL WAS CLEANED UP WITH OIL ABSORBANTS BY SCHOOL DISTRICT EMPLOYEES.  SCHOOL DISTRICT APPARENTLY MISCACULATED TANK READINGS WHEN ORDERING FUEL FROM TRIWELL. NY STATE DEPT. OF ENVIROMENTAL CONSERVATION WAS NOTIFIED AND ASSIGNED A REFERENCE # 9010242 TO THIS INCIDENT.

column168: ON DECEMBER 12, 1990 FRA INSPECTORS L. BRUCE RAMSEY AND E.P. RUDOLPH WERE MAKING INSPECTION ON YARD WHEN THEY DETECTED A SMALL VAPOR LEAK ON TANK CAR TGAX 141547.  THE CAR WAS IMMEDIATLY SET OUT TO SHOP TRACK AND SHIPPER NOTIFIED.  IT WAS FOUND TO HAVE A PIN HOLE AT A WELD REPAIR POINT ON MAN WAY COVER.  GENERAL RAILWAY SERVICE MADE REPAIRS TO THIS CAR ON DECEMBER 14, 1990.  CAR WAS THEN FORWARDED TO DESTINATION.

ON 12/06/90 AT 0740 HOURS, SENIOR SPECIAL AGENT-HAZARDOUS MATERIALS (SSA-HM) DOW LOW WAS NOTIFIED BY ANGIE GRECO, (SUPERVISOR OF YARD OPERATIONS AT DENVER, CO) THAT MECHANICAL DEPARTMENT PERSONNEL NOTED ODOR COMING FROM TANK CAR GATX 41219. TANK CAR GATX 41219 WAS ON DENVER RIP (REPAIR) TRACKS.  SSA-HM LOW'S INSPECTION REVEALED THAT THE PACKING GLAND ON THE GAUGING ROD WAS LOOSE, ALSO, THE GAUGING ROD ANGLE VALVE WAS CRACKED OPEN AND THE PIPE PLUG WAS LOOSE.  FURTHER INSPECTION REVEALED THE LIQUID AND VAPOR VALVE PIPE PLUGS WERE LOOSE.  ALL LOOSE FITTINGS WERE SECURED WHICH MITIGATED LEAKS.

column168: SENIOR SPECIAL AGENT-HAZARDOUS MATERIALS (SSA/HM) GEOFF REEDER WAS NOTIFIED OF TANK CAR PSPX 30025 LEAKING IN ANGLETON YARD, TEXAS. INSPECTION REVEALED LIQUID SEEPING FROM THE SAFETY VALVE AND ICE BUILD UP AROUND THE SAFETY VALVE.  THE GAUGING DEVICE WAS CHECKED AND INDICATED THE CAR WAS "SHELL FULL".  A PHILLIPS 66 RESPONSE TEAM, LED BY DAVE NELSON, RESPONSDED WITH A TRUCK AND OFF-LOADED 2,000 GALLONS; OUTAGE THEN READ 15". THE SAFETY VALVE RESEATED, ICE THEN MELTED AND CAR WAS REINSPECTED.  NO LEAKAGE WAS DETECTED AND CAR WAS RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT.  CHEMTREC WAS NOTIFIED (REPORT #4883).

column168: ON 12/22/90, SPECIAL AGENT-HAZARDOUS MATERIALS (SA/HM) HARRY RODABOUGH WAS NOTIFIED BY THE MANAGER OF YARD OPERATIONS OT OGDEN, UTAH, MR. JOHN LYON. MR. LYON REPORTED TANK CAR GATX 57740 LEAKING FROM THE TOP AND SPOTTED IN RAIL 13 AWAITING REPAIR. SA-HM RADABOUGH'S INSPECTION REVEALED A LOOSE MANWAY COVER PLATE AND MISAPPLIED GASKET.  THE CAR WAS WET ON TOP, HOWEVER NO EVIDENCE OF THE PRODUCT REACHING THE GROUND. SA-HM RODABOUGH REALIGNED THE GASKET AND TIGHTENED THE MANWAY COVER PLATE. THE CAR WAS MOVED AND CHECKED FOR LEAKS.  NO LEAKS NOTED AND CAR RELEASED. CHEMTREC WAS NOTIFIED (SUSAN TRACY).

DRUM PUT IN OVERSIZED RECOVERY DRUM AND PLACED IN OS&D AT COLUMBUS WAITING INSTRUCTIONS FROM SHIPPER AS TO SHIP ON OR SEND BACK.  ESTER O'NEIL AT PPG ADVISED ME TO PUT AND TO SEND ITEM BACK TO PPG ALL CLEAN UP MATERIAL INSDIE OVERSIZED DRUM.

PACKAGE BROUGHT TO REWRAP AREA.  THE BOX WAS OVERLOADED, CAUSING THE BOTTOM TO SPLIT OPEN.  MANY OF THE AEROSOL CANS, WHICH WERE INDICATED ON THE LABELS AS "FLAMMABLE", DID NOT HAVE PROTECTIVE CAPS.  THE CONTENTS OF THE BOX, WHICH INCLUDED AN ADDITIONAL 14 AEROSOL CANS TWO METAL/FRICTION-LID CONTAINERS, WERE LOADED IN A RANDOM AND LOOSE MANNER. THIS RESULTED IN THE AEROSOL CANS BUMPING INTO ONE ANOTHER, WHICH DEPRESSED THE VALVES AND RELEASED THE MATERIAL INTO THE BOX.  SPECIAL AGENT, ALEX EVANS OF THE LOCAL FEDERAL AVIATION ADMINISTRATION WAS NOTIFIED.  THE PACKAGE WAS HELD AT THE MEMPHIS HUB UNTIL RELEASED.

column168: SENIOR SPECIAL AGENT/HAZARDOUS MATERIALS (SSA/HM) DON LOW WAS CONTACTED BY DENVER SUPERVISOR OF YARD OPERATIONS THAT SWITCH ENGINE (YDE62-22), DERAILED NATX 29711.  NATX 29711 HAD WEST END TRUCKS DISCONNECTED, SHEARING OFF 4 INCHES OF BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE.  INSPECTION REVEALED THAT APPROXIMATELY 3 GALLONS PER HOUR WAS LEAKING FROM SEAT OF THE VALVE. DENVER FIRE DEPARTMENT HAZARDOUS MATERIAL TEAM, AAR/BOE INSPECTOR (RON ALBER) AND CHEMTREC WERE NOTIFIED. TANK CAR WAS RE-RAILED AND SPOTTED TO DENVER PRODUCTS TERMINAL FOR OFF-LOADING.

column42: HAZARDOUS WASTE, LIQUID OR SOLID, N.O.S.
column168: ON DECEMBER 29, 1990, OUR DRIVER L.D. REESE, WHILE WORKING IN LUBRIZOL WAS TOLD TO HAUL THE FULL NON-HAZARDOUS CONTAINER TO BFI MCCARTY LANDFILL.  AT THE LUBRIZOL LOCATION BINS THAT ARE NON-HAZARDOUS DO NOT HAVE MARKINGS TO DETERMINE THEM FROM THE HAZARDOUS WASTE BINS WHICH HAVE HAZARDOUS WASTE DECALS ON THEM. OUR DRIVER WAS NOT PAYING ATTENTION TO THE CONTAINERS AND PICKED UP A FULL CONTAINER OF BARIUM SLUDGE WITH A CLEARLY MARKED HAZARDOUS WASTE DECAL ON IT. THE DRIVER PROCEEDED TO LUBRIZOLS SECURITY GATE WHO LOOKED AT HIS PAPER WORK BUT DID NOT NOTICE HE HAD A HAZARDOUS WASTE CONTAINER ON THE TRUCK. THE SECURITY AUTHORIZED HIM TO LEAVE. UPON ARRIVAL AT FBI MCCARTY ROAD FACILITY THE PAPER WORK WAS CHECKED, HOWEVER THE CONTAINER AGAIN WAS NOT NOTICED THAT IT HAD HAZARDOUS WASTE. UPON COMPLETING THERE FINGERPRINT TEST, BFI SECURITY AUTHORIZED HIM TO DUMP THE LOAD.  WHILE DUMPING THE LOAD ANOTHER TRICIL DRIVER WHO ALSO WORKS AT LUBRIZOL NOTICED HE WAS DUMPING HAZARDOUS WASTE.  THIS DRIVER THEN IMMEDIATELY TOLD A BFI OPERATOR OF THE MISTAKE. OUR DRIVER TRIED TO GET A HOLD OF OUR DISPATCHER BUT SINCE IT WAS THE HOLIDAY SEASON THEY KEPT MISSING EACH OTHER.  THE DISPATCHER ONLY FOUND OUT ON DECEMBER 31, AT WHICH TIME BFI WAS AGAIN NOTIFIED AS WELL AS LUBRIZOL. A JOINT EFFORT CURRENTLY IS BEING MADE TO RETRIEVE THIS LOAD AND HAUL IT OFF TO THE PROPER DISPOSAL FACILITY. WE HAVE TAKEN THE FOLLOWING STEPS TO ENSURE THIS DOES NOT HAPPEN IN THE FUTURE: 1) ALL CONTAINERS WILL BE LABELED AND NUMBERED. 2) DRIVERS WILL BE DISPATCHED BY CONTAINER NUMBER. 3) CUSTOMER WILL CALL IN THE CONTAINER NUMBER TO BE HAULED, DESTINATION AND CONTENTS WHICH WILL BE ENTERED INTO OUR COMPUTER. 4) DISPATCHER WILL DISPATCH BY CONTAINER NUMBER TO THE DRIVERS. 5) AS AN ADDED PRECAUTION, BEFORE THE DRIVER LEAVES WITH THE LOAD HE HAS BEEN DISPATCHED WITH, HE WILL CALL INTO THE DISPATCHER TO VERIFY HE HAS THE CORRECT LOAD.

column42: HAZARDOUS SUBSTANCE, LIQUID OR SOLID, N.O.S. OR ORM-E, LIQUID OR SOLID, N.O.S.
column168: AT THE ORIGIN STATION TERMINAL, A LARGE "PAIL" WAS BEING UNLOADED  FROM A VAN WHEN SEEPAGE WAS OBSERVED AROUND THE TOP OF THE CONTAINER.  A MANAGER WAS NOTIFIED WHO THEN CONTACTED THE DANGEROUS GOODS HOTLINE AT FEDERAL EXPRESS IN MEMPHIS. DISCUSSIONS WITH DANGEROUS GOODS SPECIALISTS AND STATION MANAGEMENT DETERMINED THE STEEL CONTAINER WAS ACTUALLY A TELEPHONE TRANSFORMER WHICH PROBABLY CONTAINED PCB'S.  THE SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED WHO COULD NOT VERIFY THE CONTENTS WERE OR WERE NOT PCB'S.  THE SHIPPER (WALTER TART) DID STATE THAT HE DID HAVE THE TRANSFORMER FOR 30 OR 40 YEARS.  THE FAA WAS CONTACTED WHO CONTRACTED WITH CLAYTON ENGINEERING TO CONDUCT AN ANALYSIS.  CLAYTON ENVIRONMENTAL REPORTED BACK ON JANUARY 7TH THAT THE CONTENTS OF THE TRANSFORMER CONTAINED 710 PPM PCB.  I THEN INFORMED THE SHIPPER OF HIS RESPONSIBILTY FOR PROPER OFFERING OF DISPOSING OF DANGEROUS GOODS.   THIS CONTAINER WAS NOT MARKED OR INDENTIFIED IN ANY WAY AS A DANGEROUS GOODS.

column168: ON 12/29/90, WEST BOUND UNION PACIFIC TRAIN, MKTA4-27 DERAILED AT CROOKS, OREGON.  CONTAINER ON FREIGHT CAR (COFC) MAEU 239865 WAS INVOLVED.  SENIOR SPECIAL AGENT/HAZARDOUS MATERIALS (SSA/HM) D/L WHITELEY'S INSPECTION DETERMINED THAT SHIFTING FREIGHT MOVING INSIDE CONTAINER TORE OPEN TEN (10) BAGS OF CORROSIVE SOLID MATERIAL.  PRODUCT REMAINED INSIDE CONTAINER AND WAS RECOVERED.  RECOVERED PRODUCT AND DAMAGED SHIPPING BAGS WERE RETURNED TO DOW CHEMICAL.
